<div id="review_3742998668" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3742998668" />
    <a title="Alison" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7701175-alison"><img alt="Alison" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1562315654p2/7701175.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3742998668?book_show_action=true">Jan 10, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Alison" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Alison" href="/user/show/7701175-alison">Alison</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/19229075-stars-in-my-pocket-like-grains-of-sand">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7701175-alison?shelf=sf">sf</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7701175-alison?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3742998668" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6798324354002151009">There is both so much and so little to say about this one. All the criticisms are true: it is grandiose and far too wordy, what little plot there is doesn&apos;t resolve, waiting on a sequel that never came. Most characters remain cyphers, slightly unknowable to us, and possibly our protagonist. It is very much of its time, which is uneasy for sci-fi. It requires a lot of work from the reader and pays scant attention to providing easily digestible rewards. And yet, for all that, this remains kind of </span>
  <span id="freeText6798324354002151009" style="display:none">There is both so much and so little to say about this one. All the criticisms are true: it is grandiose and far too wordy, what little plot there is doesn't resolve, waiting on a sequel that never came. Most characters remain cyphers, slightly unknowable to us, and possibly our protagonist. It is very much of its time, which is uneasy for sci-fi. It requires a lot of work from the reader and pays scant attention to providing easily digestible rewards. And yet, for all that, this remains kind of magnificent, a book I am glad to have read, twice, if not a book I can honestly say I enjoy reading.<br />There are a lot of ideas packed in here - far too many, and few are really fleshed out. Much of the book is truly 'alien' - it is a struggle to understand the stylistic hybrid rituals of the Dyeth nevermind the intricate dance of a tripartite galactic power base. But these ideas coalesce around a few big ones: the ways we create and overcome social distinction, the myriad of possibilities for the ways society can work, and how it feels to move among unfamiliar mores. Delaney's concerns are about the transitory nature of categories - making his label as the father of Afrofuturism a bit weird - and he throws a dazzling array of alternatives at the audience in order to prove it. Some of the most powerful ideas now seem less shocking than they nearly four decades ago - changing pronouns and concepts of gender in particular. The breadth and audacity of his imagination however remain. <br />He could have written the second volume though.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6798324354002151009" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


