  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1986945003" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1986945003" />
    <a title="Mjhancock" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3897241-mjhancock"><img alt="Mjhancock" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1986945003?book_show_action=true">Apr 30, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mjhancock" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mjhancock" href="/user/show/3897241-mjhancock">Mjhancock</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3897241-mjhancock?shelf=sci-fi">sci-fi</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3897241-mjhancock?shelf=space-politics">space-politics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3897241-mjhancock?shelf=queer">queer</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer1986945003&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1986945003" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16323243393999504371">Like many of Delany&apos;s novels, Stars in My Pocket Like Grains of Sand feels ahead of its time, in the way it openly explores queer characters and queer desires. The book presents deeply personal perspectives within a dizzying melange of intergalactic cultures and civilizations—and yet, at times, that second half is sometimes to the book’s detriment, as it feels like it lacks a sense of unity, upon first reading. The first tenth or so of the book follows Rat Korga, a man born into poverty on the p</span>
  <span id="freeText16323243393999504371" style="display:none">Like many of Delany's novels, Stars in My Pocket Like Grains of Sand feels ahead of its time, in the way it openly explores queer characters and queer desires. The book presents deeply personal perspectives within a dizzying melange of intergalactic cultures and civilizations—and yet, at times, that second half is sometimes to the book’s detriment, as it feels like it lacks a sense of unity, upon first reading. The first tenth or so of the book follows Rat Korga, a man born into poverty on the planet Rhyonon, who agrees to allow a procedure that changes his neurological composition so he’ll accept any verbal instruction he’s given, in exchange for room and board. The novel follows his life as a slave of corporations (in Rhyonon, it’s illegal and immoral for people to own slaves, but it’s okay for corporations), emphasizing the narrowness of his existence, and the moment where it becomes something more. The rest of the book is told from the first person perspective of Marq Dyeth, an industrial diplomat who puts the “cosmos” in cosmopolitan—Dyeth’s job makes sure he* spends a lot of time communicating between denizens of a multitude of planets. The crux of the story is essentially what happens when Marq learns that he and Korga are each other’s perfect erotic match.<br />Scifi scholar Darko Suvin coined the term “novum” to describe the logically possible element of a science fiction novel that separates it from the world as we know it. In Stars in My Pocket Like Grains of Sand (heretoafter referred to as “Sand” to save my wrists) it’s near impossible to identify a single novum beyond “humanity went to the stars.” The book presents several sci-fi concepts, some common, some less so. Dyeth comes from a family that’s a mix between humans and an alien race that kind of resembles lizards, and his culture is unusual for permitting not just such families, but erotic relations between the two groups—in the north, the two are still at war. Korga’s mental clamping is another major innovation, and it’s really fascinating to see how the culture of his planet makes very, very clear distinctions between “rats” and normal people, to justify the incredible degradations that the nonrats subject him to. <br />One of the most significant cultural “nova” is the reason I put the asterisk in describing Marq as he—Marq comes from a future where our gender/sex norms have been superceded; it’s complicated, but male has become a sort of subcategory of the general concept of woman, and thus you get sentences like “The foreign male pulled off her gloves.” In that way, it reminds me very strongly of Leckie’s Ancillary series, though it came much earlier. (I should also mention that when I refer to Dveth as he, I’m not trying to countermand Delaney’s work to destabilize our gender conceptions—rather, it’s highlight that the maleness of Dyeth and Korga is an important part, for both of them, of their erotic desires.) While there are various explanations. And there’s the cultural fugue, and the conflict between Family and Sygn, which, to my detriment, I was never quite sure I got to the bottom of. Perhaps the unwritten planned sequel novel may explain some of the finer details of this universe, but for the purpose of this book, the sheer variety of unexplained difference seems to be part of Delany’s point—that from a foreign culture on a different world to the rooms of your own home, you can never entirely understand everything around you, and you need to muddle through what’s important to you, as best you can.<br />I said the story doesn’t have a novum, and while that’s mostly true, it does definitely have a unifying theme, or subject. This is somewhat both facile and generalizing, but it’s essentially a story about the overwhelming attraction between two men. And honestly, that first moment of desire, leading up to their first face-to-face meeting, is one of the most charged scenes of the book, as is Dveth’s speech at the book’s end. Beneath the veneer of far flung futures and alien culture, there’s a very clear real world analog, as two men from very different backgrounds try to connect in the time that’s given to them. Korga comes from a world where his desires weren’t unheard of, but were considered perverse; Dyeth comes from a much more permissive background, and there’s a scene that seems very true to life where he realizes his “liberal” friends are much less tolerant of his life and family than he believed. It culminates in that final Dveth speech, where Delany tips his hand—this isn’t a love story, but a story of the bit before that, about what it means to exist in cultures, in times and places, where you aren’t granted the room to explore how desire can turn into love.<br />As I said in my opening, there’s a lot of other stuff going around too, and while there’s some context, it feels like an incomplete picture, and a lot is told to us through exposition. To a certain extent, that all works, because it reinforces the centrality of Marq and Korga, but it also means that the plot lacks direction in a lot of places. (And because I had to put it somewhere, my favorite minor character is definitely Small Maxa, Marq’s young sister with a phobia towards touch.) Still, it’s a powerful narrative, and worth reading.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="16323243393999504371" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


